text:
The build loop (how LLM and code co-evolve)





flowchart LR
  A["user states intent&lt;br/&gt;(natural language)"] --&gt; B["LLM compiles → spec.yaml&lt;br/&gt;(mapping rules)"]
  B --&gt; C{"validator"}
  C --&gt;|"unknown op"| D["write one operator"]
  C --&gt;|"missing property"| E["fix spec / add requirement"]
  D --&gt; C
  E --&gt; C
  C --&gt;|"runnable"| F["engine runs"]
  F --&gt; G["verify: intent +&lt;br/&gt;repeatability + well-formed"]
  G --&gt; H["archive.py records&lt;br/&gt;spec + seed + metrics + thumb"]







user states intent in natural language;
LLM compiles → spec.yaml (following the mapping rules);
validator runs: unknown op → write one operator; missing property → fix spec or add the requirement; else it is runnable;
engine runs; verify checks intent + repeatability + well-formedness;
archive.py records spec + seed + metrics + thumb into the gallery;
new capability → one new registered operator (+ its REQUIRES_*), never an engine edit.

Qualitatively different collective behaviours, all produced from the same code by changing only a ~20-line specification — no new software per phenomenon.





